Great place to stop for a quick sandwich or yogurt... But I feel it's worth avoiding any drink that requires a barista to make it. The barista who made my latte desperately needs some training. The scalding temperature of milk is 180F, and ideal temps for a frothed milk in a latte are between 140F-158F. My drink was in the ballpark of 190F, possibly on the verge of boiling. Not only does that make for a terrible tasting drink, but that puts the customer at risk of a nasty burn.  To give some perspective of how overheated the milk was, I was able to eat my sandwich in the shop, walk to Lafayette Square, find a coffee shop over there, order a new latte, and drink the other latte before this one hit drinkable temperatures. Once this drink did reach drinkable temps it was so awful tasting that it had to be thrown away.  Based on other reviews, it sounds like this place can make a good drink. But the person who made mine definitely needs to start using a thermometer while frothing their milk.

It's a shame, because the staff is really great, the food is a fresh getaway from the pubs and heavy seafood of the rest of D.C, but seating is typically cramped. It's a popular, crowded place, so my best recommendation would be to get this to go. Space is a luxury here, true, so maybe catch a bus down to a green space or the Mall to enjoy your delicious food.  Major kudos, though, to Pret a Manger for their commitment to sustainability and recycling. All their plasticware is fully recyclable, and everything else can be thrown into compost.
